Title: Owner of a Lonely Heart
Comment:
Ring name: CoCo McGoGo

Persona: I'd come out dressed as an old wizard. I'd walk slowly with a cane then as I get to the ring the ref lifts my cloak to reveal... An even older, more frail wizard. The shock value would make my opponent faint immediately.

Finishing move: With my opponent already on the ground I would pull a Fairlight CMI from my tattered wizard hat and rip that bitchin' sampled orchestra hit solo while giving a slow wink to the camera as it zooms in.

Title: Sabotage
Comment: Taking inspo from the music video my wrestling character would be a corrupt 70s cop called Dirk "The Moustache" Malone. Finishing move would be an illegal choke hold called "the resisting arrest". I would have a tag team partner who plays a criminal and our team name would be Opposites Attack.

Title: Blame It On Bad Luck
Comment:
I will be Nuerotix, a heel/career jobber with a character centered on being a disaffected punkass and total killjoy. This won't be my entrance at the start of my career as that character, though. This comes in as part of my later face turn, when the character shifts from "oh woe is me" to "yeah, woe IS me, but I'm still taking that belt" and I drop "Neurotix" for a normal human name.

My in-ring style is best described as "bad." I was hired for the mic. Dave Meltzer wants to kill me.

Title: The Rascal King
Comment:
Ring Name: The Rascal King

Persona: A charismatic showman. This cunning underdog is always willing to bend the rules to win, with a flair for dramatic comebacks and a loyal fanbase.

Signature Move: The Boston Bribe - The King distracts opponents with a fake bribe, then swiftly ensnares them in a decisive lock, leaving one arm free to kiss babies.

Finishing Move: The Celtic Comeback - After a dramatic build-up, faking a fall, The King knots up his opponent and takes them to the ground.

Title: Bitch Bites Dog
Album: Plucking a Cherry From The Void
Comment:
My wrestling alter-ego is a lovable heel called "Bitch Cassidy", a flamboyant, peacocking Dalton Castle type (revealed to the brother & half-brother (respectively) of Orange Cassidy & Isiah Kassidy in an upcoming AEW storyline).

My finisher is also called the "Bitch Bites Dog" - I hang my opponent over the top rope in a kind of Downward Dog pose, vault onto the top rope either side of them, and as their momentum tips them backwards I straddle their neck and Poisonrana them back into the ring.

Title: Scrappers
Comment:
Cut me some slack because I know nothing about wrestling and I'm experiencing brainrot from like 30 straight hours of working on a "group" project that was mostly watching my group do it all wrong and me correcting it.
This song has good entrance music energy, and I think The Scrapper would be a cool name to go along with it. His finishing move could be the ultimate sucker punch or something. That's where my creativity runs out at the moment. Fuck group projects.

Title: Get Ready
Comment: Like my wrestler self, this song is retro and a little campy and will surely get the crowd going!

Title: Maneater
Comment: My wrestler persona would be The Maneater, who is definitely a heel but in a sort of anti-hero way, taking revenge on all the evil male wrestlers. As I walk to the ring, "everybody look at me, me" would blast out and the audience rooting for me will cheer "you wish you never ever met her at all". Finishing move would be Around the World, where I jump from the ropes and bring people to the matt with my legs around their neck. Of course thigh high boots are an essential part of my costume

Title: No Money To Love You
Comment: I don't watch wrestling, but I do think my gimmick would have to be doing anything necessary to get some cash money. Being a heel, a fall guy, winning the whole thing, whatever it takes. Maybe have a name that reflects that, 'Solid Gold' or something

Title: Dog House
Comment: My ring name would be Mx Mongrel and my whole thing would be dog themed but like super gay and cunty. My persona would be like if Paris Hilton had rabies and my outfit would be black and pink with glittery dog motifs, including a rhinestone collar. My finishing move would be called the JUGULAR CRUSHER where I bite my opponents throat and mangle them. I don't know how wrestling works

Title: Neat Neat Neat
Comment: My ring name is "Dr. Boy." I'm a renegade med student with so much student loan debt that I've got less than nothing to lose. My finishing move is called "the stethoscope," and without describing it too graphically I can guarantee your hearing will never be the same afterwords.

Title: Hey Big Man
Comment:
This song has everything you would need for an intimidating entrance - angry vocal delivery, a banger beat, and a mention of ur mom 

My ring name would be Big Bully Billy 
I would wear a big belt that has an engraved human centipede all around 
For my finishing move, I’d climb up in the corner of the ring, shotgun that beer, scream, jump and turn my opponent into a pancake 
Then I’d bounce in the ring like a mattress as my victory dance

Title: Right Back to It
Comment: Video:  https://youtu.be/YL3iHhERWJw?si=hc3MF41CWmVnqVyL Visually gorgeous. For a song about the journey of a stable long-term relationship, the video’s motion and vibe are stable, gliding, and comfortable. Very fitting on all counts. The scenery is unmistakably Southern (filmed on a lake between Louisiana and Texas). I’ve loved every Waxahatchee era but think it’s especially cool how she’s embraced her roots with the a more country-inflected sound and vocals on more recent albums.

Title: Taken Care Of
Comment:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H2qb0gb-WZ4

I'm a sucker for a one-take music video. This one seems to vibe with the song's themes of being young, unsupervised and a bit feral growing up in the city. 

Suzi says - "The video is a surreal look at an early morning walk home through London. I wanted to show a disconnect between youth and their parents – what does your little darling get up to at night?"

It feels like them doing an elliott smith cover should have absolutely been on my radar but it wasn’t for a long time. Kind of a weird album, not how I picture the band at all, down to the artwork, but really good cover.

Title: Llorando Se Fue
Comment: Hear me out, going for the inverse of “unlikely cover” here. Two days ago I heard the 1989 song “Kambada” by Kaoma for the first time and was shocked that it totally sounded like “Taboo” (2011) by Don Omar, which was like my favorite song at Zumba. But wait! That wasn’t the original either. I then learned about the existence of THIS Bolivian folk song. Pretty sure it’s finally the original. Credit where credit is due! Kaoma also apparently got in legal trouble for copying. The melody is 🔥🔥

Title: Cotton Eyed Joe - Mono; Single Edit; 2017 Remaster

Title: 500 Years
Comment: Against Me is one of my favorite bands of all time, but I just found this song for the first time a couple of days ago. I know it doesn't really fit the weird/out of characters aspect, but I couldn't think of anything that does

Title: Time Machine
Comment: Okay, so this Logic album is the least popular and least well known because he diverged from his usual rap and hip hop to create an album where he (mostly) sings. The album accompanies a book of the same name and is meant to be a pair with it. Hardcore Logic fans will know this album but not most people (and a lot of fans have forgotten about it or refuse to listen to it because it doesn't feel like him). Personally, I really enjoy the album and I think he has a great singing voice.

Title: The First Cut is the Deepest
Comment: I recently was part of a charity set that involved covering a ton of Sheryl Crow songs. I always thought 'The First Cut is the Deepest' was a Rod Stewart cover, but it turns out both Stewart and Crow were covering P.P Arnold's forgotten hit from 1968. Wild times.

fuck me this goes haaard. one time in december 2012 it came on shuffle on my headphones while i was deep in a heartbroken chasm and kind of instantly defibrillated me back into a functioning self-respecting human. thanks S-K!

Title: never meant
Comment:
8294 listeners

maybe it's blasphemy to cover/sample this song in this style, but given the recent trend of hyperpop artists pairing twiddly midwest emo-style riffs with thuddy 808s and skittery beats, this feels like something that was always on the cards (and i'm glad it was holliday that finally did it - check out https://www.youtube.com/shorts/MqWFr90WtjU for her production how-to). 

the build-up/breakdown bit around 1.10 is so good, and vindicates the choice to do it in this style for me.

Title: I Feel Better
Album: Tiny Changes: A Celebration of Frightened Rabbit's 'The Midnight Organ Fight'
Comment: 2,271 monthly listeners. From an excellent multi-artist tribute album for Frightened Rabbit after Scott Hutchison’s tragic death. Perky music, dark lyrics. Strikes the ideal cover balance: Works in just enough of its subtle own musical spin to be interesting while staying faithful to the original

Title: Haley
Comment: I don’t know how to explain this song other than it is the musical equivalent of how I feel when eating Cinnamon Toast Crunch. If you think this is too elegant for that cereal, you’re eating it wrong.

Title: Grace Kelly
Comment: Saturday morning cereal to me makes me immediately think of being a kid and we would go off on holidays in our campervan and this song was one that I strongly associate with one holiday in France, me and my brother Daniel having not a care in the world other than eating our Rice Krispies, jumping on our bikes to cycle our version of the Tour de France (3 laps round the park), then off to the pool to hear this song on repeat for the evening. Great memories

Title: We Can Work It Out
Comment:
This particular cover feels like positivity and possibility to me, which is an ideal way to start the weekend. The cereal that I’m eating is Raisin Bran Crunch. 
Both the song and the cereal are sweet without being overly saccharine, have varied textures, and feel energizing while satiating. 
I’m definitely dancing in my kitchen between spoonfuls

Title: Welcome to My World
Comment: I know he says applejacks in the song, but I'm eating peanut butter crunch

Title: Sunshine Superman
Comment: A lightly groovy and hopeful tune for the morning. Listen to it while eating whatever type of cereal was eaten in the 1960s. Wait, I looked it up just for you: “Quisp, a pink-skinned alien in a green jumpsuit, became a madly popular character for the space age. He fought his rival, the miner Quake, in a series of commercials.” It is a saucer-shaped cereal from Quaker and now I kinda want to try it.

Title: HEAVEN TO ME
Album: CALL ME IF YOU GET LOST: The Estate Sale
Comment: This song always fills me with a sense of hope and peace. I eat Honey Nut Cheerios because they're superior than any other cereal. With some berries and vanilla almond milk? Incredible. Gonna have that tomorrow morning.

Title: Big Time Sensuality

Title: Kool Aid & Frozen Pizza
Comment: Saturday morning cereal is laid-back, chill, and also kind of adolescent. I think this Mac album is a perfect vibe fit for this. I could also see having Kool-Aid and frozen pizza as the next meal after cereal.  The cereal in question, of course, would be Reese's Puffs.

Title: Whipped Cream Daydream
Comment:
cereal is for rushed weekday mornings; at the weekend there's time for something slower and a bit more special, and while there's still been a chill in the air i've been partaking in some rather luxurious porridge (or "oatmeal", if you will) that teeters very close to dessert territory - a rich, creamy slop feat. sultanas and orange blossom water and topped with a little crumbled brownie, orange marmalade and a slick of cream. 

this song is the musical equivalent.

Title: Sé Lest
Comment:
For the first 6 minutes it's all twinkly instruments, celestial vocals and the odd orchestral swell - so far so Sigur Ros (feel free to skim forward). 

Then some brass instruments gradually enter, but it's nothing they've not done before. We're still safe, we're in Iceland, we know what to expect....

.....but wait......are they taking us to.......to Germany? 

(It's not exactly a jump-scare, but by Sigur Ros standards it's a very silly and unlikely genre-deviation within a song).
